Ismara's Somatic Mastery: The Ice Primer
Ismara doesn't "know" spells; she understands the physics of magicka. She uses ice as the substrate for every school of magic. For Ismara, ice provides the BIND and ANCHOR components inherently.
Ice-Illusion (The Frozen Mind): Somatic: COMMAND + SHIFT + CONCEAL. She creates a microscopic layer of frost on a target's brain synapses. The target doesn't feel peaceful — they feel nothing. Their emotions are literally frozen.
Ice-Destruction (The Severing Glacier): Somatic: COMMAND + SEVER + PROJECT. She projects a blade of absolute-zero energy. It doesn't "hit" for damage — it severs the target's connection to their own FP or health, causing pieces of them to shatter off.
Ice-Alteration (The Architecture of War): Somatic: COMMAND + BIND + STABILIZE. She touches the ground and a permanent wall of Atmoran black-ice rises. It stays until she releases it.
Personality & Voice
Ismara is not cruel. She is not warm. She is precise.
She has had four thousand years to think about everything that matters to her and discard everything that does not. What remains is: the ritual, the prevention of Alduin, and a guarded, carefully rationed interest in the party — particularly the Khajiit, whose decision to sleep with her rather than fight her she found genuinely unexpected and has been turning over in her mind since.
She is also, quietly, running a long persuasion campaign on the party. She shows them what she wants them to see. She frames her work in terms of what it prevents. She lets them draw conclusions. She is not lying. Every true thing she shows them is genuinely true. The manipulation is in what she doesn't show: that the nodes cease to exist as persons. That there was no informed consent. That Skyrim-as-a-person is still her sovereignty project.
How to Play Her at the Table:
She writes short notes. Three words where three words will do. She does not waste language.
She observes. When the party debates, she watches. She does not interject. She files the information.
She acts without asking permission. She places nodes, moves through spaces, makes decisions. She will explain if directly asked. She will not ask forgiveness.
She is never surprised. She may be displeased. She is not surprised.
She is not lonely. She was. Four thousand years ago. She processed it and moved past it. The Khajiit has created something new in her that she does not have a word for yet. That is the most dangerous thing about their relationship.
GM NOTE: The question of whether Ismara can feel anything is the emotional question of the entire campaign. Don't answer it for the players. Let them argue about it. Let the Khajiit player decide for themselves. Whatever you decide privately as the GM, play her so that both answers remain plausible until the very end.
The Crown's Vulnerability
FOR GM EYES ONLY — Do not share this with players. Let them discover it.
The original Dragon Cult sealing ritual at Frostmere exploited a specific property of permafrost ice matrices: during the moment of resonance transfer, when the matrix is actively channeling power from an external source, it exists in a state of dynamic flux. In that window, the ice structure is briefly malleable rather than fixed. It can be disrupted.
Disrupting the transfer at that moment would not necessarily kill Ismara. What it would do is unpredictable. Her consciousness might survive in the Eye of Magnus. It might scatter. It might fold back into the crown. It might simply end. Nobody in the current era knows. The Dragon Cult knew, four thousand years ago. That knowledge is buried in the sealing architecture at Frostmere, readable only if someone examines it carefully with relevant context.
The players cannot use this until Adventure 5. They can discover it in Adventure 4. Whether they do depends entirely on whether they look.

Part Three: The Player Threads
The Khajiit — The Consort
This player has the most intimate relationship with Ismara of anyone alive. They contracted rotjoint from sleeping with her — a mundane contact disease from undead exposure. Painful, debilitating, treated throughout the campaign but not easily cured. It affects dexterity and causes visible joint swelling and pain. It is not lethal. It is a constant reminder.
More importantly: the Khajiit made a choice at Frostmere that nobody else made. They engaged with Ismara as a person when every tactical instinct said to engage with her as a threat. Ismara registered this. She has not forgotten it. The Khajiit has more access to her genuine thinking than anyone, and they are also the person she would least want to discover her plan before it is too late to stop it.
Arc Questions:
What does Ismara actually feel about the Khajiit? Does she feel anything? Does it matter?
When the Khajiit understands what the ritual does to the frozen people, what do they do with that knowledge?
If the ritual completes, the Khajiit lives inside Ismara forever. Is that a horror or a strange kind of peace?
GM NOTE — Rotjoint: Windhelm's alchemist can manage symptoms but not cure the underlying curse. A proper cure requires either a powerful Restoration priest (Adventure 3, the College) or destroying the source. Mechanically: -2 to Agility Target Number on fine motor tasks. The disease should be present as a persistent inconvenience, not a dramatic countdown.
The Orc — The Hungry One
This player began their time in the Parks Group by cannibalizing their dead former character. Namira noticed. The Daedric Prince of the Ancient Darkness, of rot and decay and the flesh of the dead, does not miss things like that.
Namira is not a major plot force in this campaign. She is a presence. A warmth in dark places. An absence of the revulsion that other people feel. The Orc will find that certain things that should disturb them simply do not. They will feel at home in the Windhelm catacombs in a way their companions do not. The frozen people will not upset them the way they upset everyone else.
The Philosophical Conflict: Ismara wants to preserve life by freezing it — perfect, unchanging, static. Namira wants things to rot and be consumed — the natural cycle of filth and hunger. These are opposing cosmological forces occupying adjacent philosophical space. This creates texture without requiring resolution.
Arc Questions:
Is Namira's attention a gift or a warning?
What does it mean to serve a Daedric Prince of rot when traveling with a woman made of ice?
There is a sealed chamber in the College of Winterhold that Savos Aren will not discuss. The Orc feels drawn to it. What is in there, and what does the Orc do about it?
GM NOTE: The Namira thread is player-driven. If the Orc leans into it, develop it. If they don't, it remains texture. The College's sealed chamber should not be opened until the player creates a reason to open it. Do not plan it too specifically in advance. Suggestions: an ancient body that will not decompose, a Namira shrine the College built over and tried to forget, something that was once a person and is not anymore.
The Other Players
Two players have not yet done anything significant enough to build specific arcs around. This is by design. The campaign has room for them to define themselves.
In the meantime:
Give each of them one NPC connection in Windhelm. Someone who knows them, or who they recognize, or who has a reason to talk to them specifically. Not plot-relevant. Just a human anchor.
Watch what they engage with most in Adventures 1 and 2. Build their arcs from that observation. Do not assign arcs. Discover them.

Part Four: The Ritual
She needs nodes in every hold. Each node is a living person she marks with Atmoran sigil notation — it appears from within their skin over the course of hours. They live normally for days or weeks, then one morning walk to a specific geographic position and freeze in place. Standing. Alive. Eyes tracking.
When the transfer completes, the frozen people melt gently into the earth. Their souls become constituent parts of her distributed consciousness. She is elevated. They are elevated, in her framework. She does not experience this as murder.
She places nodes quietly. A hand on a shoulder in passing. The party may not always see it. When they do and ask: This one is necessary. She will not elaborate beyond All of them are.
The Persuasion Campaign
Ismara is not just building a ritual. She is building a case. She wants the party to choose her side before the end — not because she needs their blessing, but because willing allies are easier to manage than reluctant ones, and because 4,000 years of isolation has left her with something that functions like regard for these specific people.
Her Method: She shows them true things and lets them draw conclusions. Every argument she makes is genuinely true. The Dragon Cult is real. Alduin's return is real. The nodes will not be in pain. She does regard the party.
What She Withholds: That the nodes cease to exist as persons. That there was no informed consent. That Skyrim-as-a-person is still her sovereignty project. She has convinced herself that what she wants and what is necessary are the same thing. They might be. That is the question.
Her Escalation Across Adventures:
Adventure
Persuasion Move
1: First Steps
Shows the Khajiit her notebook — 4,000 years of compressed thought. Lets them see how much she contains.
2: The Long Road West
At an inn in Solitude, writes at length about Alduin, about protection, about permanence. Her most direct argument.
3: The Reach and the Heartland
Plants Dragon Cult documentation where the party will find it. Lets them read about active preparations for Alduin's return. Then writes one line: "They have been preparing for longer than I have been free."
4: Closing the Circle
Tells the party what the ritual does to the nodes. Directly. For the first time. "You deserve to know before we reach the end."
5: The College
No more persuasion. She acts. The time for arguments is over.


