What Is Actually Happening:
Two holds remain. Then the Eye. Ismara's behavior shifts — less conversational, more focused. She is beginning to show the party something closer to what she actually is. Not the measured diplomat. The being who has been running this calculation for four thousand years and is watching it move toward completion.
Falkreath: The Dragon Cult has agents here. This is the campaign's first planned combat encounter — 3–5 agents, fast and brutal. Ismara kills with architectural precision. The first time the party sees her fight at full capability should be genuinely alarming.
Riften: In Riften, Ismara tells them the part she has been withholding. She writes:
When the transfer is complete, the nodes will melt into the earth. They will become part of what I am. They will not cease. They will be permanent in a way nothing mortal is permanent. I know you will not see this as I see it. I am telling you because you deserve to know before we reach the end.
The party now has the complete picture.
The Return to Frostmere — The Critical Discovery:
While Ismara works in the throne room ruins, the party can examine the sealing architecture of the original Dragon Cult ritual. What is readable, to someone who has been paying attention:
The Dragon Cult used the crown's own architecture against her. They exploited the dynamic flux state of permafrost ice matrices during resonance transfer. In that window the matrix is malleable. They initiated a false transfer, drew the crown into flux, collapsed it. She was frozen between states.
The implication is not labeled. It is just there, in the structure of the trap, for someone who is looking.
GM NOTE: This is the most important discovery in the campaign. It gives the party a theoretical option they did not have before. Do not flag it for them. Do not have it glow or be labeled. If they find it, they earned it.
Ending: The central node is complete. Ismara writes: It is nearly time. The College. I will need a few days. Then she writes one more thing: You have served well. All of you. I will remember this. For Ismara, this is profound.

