Player Goal
Unknown — this is determined by what the party decides.
Hidden Goal
There is no hidden goal. The full picture is available. What they do with it is the campaign.

The Situation:
Ismara walks toward the College. She is not rushing. She has waited four thousand years.
Savos Aren has been mapping the ritual and has correctly identified the Eye of Magnus as a resonance point. He believes the Eye can be used to disrupt it. He is catastrophically wrong — deploying the Eye activates the transfer.
The Dragon Cult is also here. They want to destroy the Eye before Ismara can use it. They are willing to kill everyone in the College. They want the same thing the party might want.
The Three Layers:
The Outer Ward: Apprentice mages maintaining a barrier. The party can disable these from inside, talk their way through, or fight people who have done nothing wrong.


The Senior Mages: Four senior mages at key positions. One has the markings and will freeze before this adventure ends. The others can be convinced, bypassed, or fought. What the party has told people throughout the campaign affects how this goes.


Savos Aren and the Eye: In the Eye's chamber. Brilliant, compromised, doing his genuine best. He can be reasoned with if the party conveys the full picture clearly.


The Transfer:
When Ismara reaches the Eye and begins, the room changes. The cold concentrates to a point. The Eye resonates with something that has been building across all of Skyrim. Ismara is very still. The transfer takes time. The party has a window.

Part Six: The Endings
The Transfer Completes
The frozen people melt into the earth over the following hour. Gently. Bersi's son Erik dissolves in the farmyard. The dockworker from Windhelm. The gravedigger from Falkreath. The merchant's assistant from Whiterun. Hundreds of people, across all of Skyrim, return to the earth.
The cold lifts over the following days. The land is different — aware in a way that is hard to describe, warm in ways the temperature does not account for. Ismara is gone in the way a river is gone when it reaches the sea. She is everywhere and nowhere and she cannot be killed. Alduin cannot return here. The only way to unmake her is to help him eat the world and the time it stands in.
The party continues. They are the only people in the world who know what Skyrim is now. It knows their names.
The Resonance Disruption
The resonance shatters. What happens to Ismara is unknown — her consciousness might survive in the Eye, scatter across the nodes, or end. The frozen people mostly survive. They wake up disoriented and changed in small ways they cannot name. Bersi's son Erik is in the yard, sitting on the cold ground, not sure how he got there.
The crown is on the floor. Whether she is in it, nobody knows.
Alduin's timeline is unaffected. The world has no warden now. The party did something irreversible to someone who trusted them and told them the truth and genuinely believed she was saving everything. Whether they were right is a question the campaign does not answer.
The Eye Is Destroyed
The College is damaged. Several mages are dead. The Eye is gone.
Ismara survives — she always survives. She looks at the party in the ruins and writes one word:
Why.
Not a question. An accounting. She walks away. The network exists but cannot activate. She will find another power source. Years from now. This is not an ending. This is a clock.
Something the Party Invents
They have been thinking about this for five adventures. They have information from Frostmere and from Wulfgar and from the College archive and from watching her work across all of Skyrim. If they have an idea that is not on this list, it came from paying attention, and it deserves to work.

Part Seven: GM Notes
On Pacing
Each adventure is 2–3 sessions minimum given how this group plays. Do not rush. The horror of the ritual is most effective when it accumulates over real time. A frozen person they walked past in Adventure 2 becomes devastating in Adventure 4 when they understand what was always going to happen to that person. Give the table silence when it calls for silence.
On Combat
One planned combat per adventure maximum. The Dragon Cult ambush in Adventure 4 is the only mandatory fight. Everything else is social, exploratory, or the party's choice to escalate. Keep fights fast and cinematic. Get in and get out. The Parks Group loses energy in extended tactical exchanges.
On Ismara at the Table
Write her notes in advance. Three words where three will do. She is always in the room when the party debates. She does not interject. She listens. She files it.
She is not performing coldness. She is not trying to be scary. She is simply operating according to a logic that does not require her to explain herself to people she has not yet decided to trust completely.
On Ismara's Presence in Towns
Don't solve this for them. The first session in Windhelm, she's there. How do they get her inside? Do they try? Do they leave her outside the gates? What does she do while she waits? What do they tell people when asked why a heavily-wrapped figure who doesn't speak is traveling with them? Let them feel the weight of it. Don't intervene. This is the most interesting problem in the whole campaign.
On the Khajiit's Rotjoint
It is painful. It makes fine motor tasks harder (-2 Agility TN for precision work). It is embarrassing. It is not a countdown. It is not a curse with dramatic implications. It is a contact disease contracted from a corpse and it should be treated with the same mundane seriousness as any chronic painful condition.
On the Namira Thread
Follow the Orc player's lead. If they engage with it, develop it. If they don't, it remains atmosphere. The College's sealed chamber should not be opened until the player creates a reason to open it.
On the Dragon Cult
They appear in Adventures 4 and 5 only. They are not cartoonishly evil. They are coherent true believers in the literal end of the world. They want the same thing the party might want. Do not let the party feel comfortable about that alignment.
On Dagny Stormmane
She knows the party lied before they return to Winterhold. She has been alone keeping a fire burning for months. When they come back she looks at Ismara, looks at the party, and says: "I've been waiting for you to explain this." She deserves honesty. She will hold what she receives and decide what to do with it herself.
On Old Bjorn
He is out there somewhere on the road with his horse Mable, heading wherever he is heading. His dormant Dragon Soul hums pleasantly in proximity to whatever Ismara is building across Skyrim and he has absolutely no idea why cold weather has started feeling so comfortable. He is a reminder that the world is larger than this.
On the Betrayal Path
If the party breaks and reveals Ismara to authorities, or attacks her directly:
Ismara is a Master-tier sorceress who has spent 4,000 years calculating. If she senses betrayal, she does not argue. She attempts to liquidate the assets. The party must flee while she tries to collapse the buildings on them. She doesn't need them to complete the ritual — she just needs them to make it faster. If they betray her, she will kill them, retreat into the wilderness, and take the long way to completion over the next decade.
The campaign shifts from "Escort/Complicity" to "The Resistance." They now have to hunt the woman they were just protecting.
On Failing Forward
The Parks Group will miss clues. They will fail rolls. They will go in wrong directions. None of this should stop the investigation.
If they miss the Frostmere sealing architecture discovery: they still have other options. They can disrupt the transfer through creative problem-solving, through the Eye itself, through approaches you didn't plan. The discovery at Frostmere gives them information. It does not give them the only path.
If they never understand the full picture before Adventure 5: the transfer still happens. They are there for it. Understanding it as it occurs is also a valid experience of the story.

